According to the [[Book of Mormon]], a [[sacred text]] of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], '''Cezoram''' ({{IPAc-en|s|iː|ˈ|z|ɔːr|ə|m}})<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from «sē-zōr´um»</ref> was the eighth Nephite chief judge (c. 30 BC).  In the 62nd year of the [[Nephites#Judges|reign of the judges]], or 30 BC, [[Nephi, son of Helaman]], gave up the judgement seat and thence devoted himself to spreading the gospel.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Helaman|chapter=5|verse=1|range=}}</ref>  Four years later, in 26 BC, Cezoram was murdered by the [[Gadianton robbers]].  His son replaced him, but was murdered also.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Helaman|chapter=6|verse=15|range=}}</ref> After that, the government fell into the hands of those robbers,<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Helaman|chapter=6|verse=38|range=-39}}</ref> and it is not known what happened with the judgement-seat until [[Nephi, son of Helaman|Nephi]] came back to call the people to repentance.<ref>{{Sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Helaman|chapter=8|verse=27|range=ff}}</ref> (Cezoram is distinct from the similarly named Gadianton robber [[Seezoram]].)

