[[File:Miguel Piernavieja del Pozo.jpg|thumb|Miguel Piernavieja del Pozo]] {{spanish name|Piernavieja}} '''Miguel Piernavieja del Pozo''' (21 May 1916 – 8 June 1983)<ref name="rah.es" /> was a Spanish spy for [[Nazi Germany]], operating in Britain during the [[Second World War]]. He was quickly spotted by the [[MI5|Security Services]] (MI5) who gave him the codename ''Pogo'' and used one of their double-agents to feed him [[disinformation]] which was relayed to the Germans.
== Spanish Civil War == Born in [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]] on 21 May 1916,<ref name="rah.es">{{cite book |title=[[Diccionario Biográfico Español]]|author=Real Academia de la Historia|authorlink=Real Academia de la Historia |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=10 January 2015|quote=Santa Cruz de Tenerife 21.V.1916 – Madrid 8.VI.1983}}</ref> Piernavieja was a [[Falangism|Falangist]] who had worked for [[Francisco Franco]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]].<ref name="Burns">{{cite book|last=Burns|first= Jimmy|title=Papa Spy: A True Story of Love, Wartime Espionage in Madrid, and the Treachery of the Cambridge Spies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vYbz8bvsNjMC&pg=PT177|year=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London|isbn=978-1-4088-2773-4|page=177}}</ref><ref name="ELPAIS">{{cite journal|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2009/11/01/domingo/1257051158_850215.html |title=Anacletos de Franco |first= Walter |last=Oppenheimer |date=1 November 2009 |journal=El País |publisher= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>
== Spying in Britain == In 1940,<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article4246171.ece "MI5 found dissolute Spaniard all too easy to deceive."] David Sanderson, ''[[The Times]]'', 24 October 2014. Retrieved 10 January 2015. {{subscription required}}</ref> the [[List of diplomatic missions of the United Kingdom|British Embassy]] in [[Madrid]], with the personal recommendation of British ambassador [[Samuel Hoare, 1st Viscount Templewood|Samuel Hoare]], arranged for Piernavieja to travel to Britain as an observer for a Madrid-based study group.<ref name="Hennessey1904">{{cite book|last=Hennessey|first=Thomas |title=Spooks: The Unofficial History of MI5 from Agent Zig Zag to the D-Day Deception 1939-45|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wDKIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT97|date=1 January 1904|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|isbn=978-1-4456-0800-6|pages=97–99}}</ref><ref name="revistaEclectica">{{cite journal|first=Antonio César |last=Moreno Cantano |url=http://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/3904118.pdf|title=Propaganda y espionaje franquista en Gran Bretaña durante la Segunda Guerra Mundial |trans-title=Francoist propaganda and espionage in Britain during World War II|issn= 2254-0113 |language=Spanish |journal=Ecléctica, Revista de estudios culturales |year=2012 | volume=1 |pages= 81–91 |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> He arrived in Britain on 29 September 1940.<ref name="Burns" /><ref name="Diario de Las Palmas">{{cite news|url=http://www.laprovincia.es/sociedad/2013/01/20/espia-canario-londres/509747.html |title=Un espía canario en Londres |author= |date= |website= |journal=La Provincia – Diario de Las Palmas |accessdate=10 January 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Piernavieja was contacted by Gwylm Williams, who had tried to work for the Germans in 1939 but had been recruited as a [[double-agent]] by MI5 instead.<ref name="The National Archives">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/news/german-intelligence-agents-suspected-agents-oct-14.htm |title=Miguel Piernavieja del Pozo, aliases Pogo, Pojo (2/10/1940-09/11/1945) |author= [[National Archives (UK)|The National Archives]] |date= |website= German Intelligence Agents and suspected agents |publisher= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="Andrew2010">{{cite book|last=Andrew|first=Christopher M. |title=The Defence of the Realm: The Authorized History of MI5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNxDAQAAIAAJ|date=June 2010|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-102330-4|pages=259–261}}</ref> Williams posed as an ardent [[Welsh nationalism|Welsh nationalist]] and Piernavieja gave him £3900 (a sum more than 10x the average annual wage<ref name="Field">{{cite book|last=Field|first=Geoffrey G. |title=Blood, Sweat, and Toil: Remaking the British Working Class, 1939–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4ZjYbhPxpIC&pg=PA120|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-960411-1|page=120}}</ref>) in a talcum-powder tin and asked him to obtain information on the Welsh nationalist movement and on factories making munitions in the west of England. According to Williams, Piernavieja had asked him to make plans for sabotage.<ref name="Burns" />
== War service == Piernavieja was awarded the [[Iron Cross]] for his military service in the [[Division Azul]] on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].<ref name="The National Archives"/> He returned to Spain in January 1941.<ref name="Diario de Las Palmas" />
